 10  # Smooth manifolds (possibly with boundary or corners)
 11  
 12  A smooth manifold is a manifold modelled on a normed vector space, or a subset like a
 13  half-space (to get manifolds with boundaries) for which the change of coordinates are smooth maps.
 14  We define a model with corners as a map `I : H â†’ E` embedding nicely the topological space `H` in
 15  the vector space `E` (or more precisely as a structure containing all the relevant properties).
 16  Given such a model with corners `I` on `(E, H)`, we define the groupoid of local
 17  homeomorphisms of `H` which are smooth when read in `E` (for any regularity `n : with_top â„•`).
 18  With this groupoid at hand and the general machinery of manifolds, we thus get the notion of `C^n`
 19  manifold with respect to any model with corners `I` on `(E, H)`. We also introduce a specific type
 20  class for `C^âˆ` manifolds as these are the most commonly used.
 21  
 22  ## Main definitions
 23  
 24  * `model_with_corners ğ•œ E H` :
 25    a structure containing informations on the way a space `H` embeds in a
 26    model vector space E over the field `ğ•œ`. This is all that is needed to
 27    define a smooth manifold with model space `H`, and model vector space `E`.
 28  * `model_with_corners_self ğ•œ E` :
 29    trivial model with corners structure on the space `E` embedded in itself by the identity.
 30  * `times_cont_diff_groupoid n I` :
 31    when `I` is a model with corners on `(ğ•œ, E, H)`, this is the groupoid of local homeos of `H`
 32    which are of class `C^n` over the normed field `ğ•œ`, when read in `E`.
 33  * `smooth_manifold_with_corners I M` :
 34    a type class saying that the manifold `M`, modelled on the space `H`, has `C^âˆ` changes of
 35    coordinates with respect to the model with corners `I` on `(ğ•œ, E, H)`. This type class is just
 36    a shortcut for `has_groupoid M (times_cont_diff_groupoid âŠ¤ I)`.
 37  * `ext_chart_at I x`:
 38    in a smooth manifold with corners with the model `I` on `(E, H)`, the charts take values in `H`,
 39    but often we may want to use their `E`-valued version, obtained by composing the charts with `I`.
 40    Since the target is in general not open, we can not register them as local homeomorphisms, but
 41    we register them as local equivs. `ext_chart_at I x` is the canonical such local equiv around `x`.
 42  
 43  As specific examples of models with corners, we define (in the file `real_instances.lean`)
 44  * `euclidean_space n` for a model vector space of dimension `n`.
 45  * `model_with_corners â„ (euclidean_space n) (euclidean_half_space n)` for the model space used
 46  to define `n`-dimensional real manifolds with boundary and
 47  * `model_with_corners â„ (euclidean_space n) (euclidean_quadrant n)` for the model space used
 48  to define `n`-dimensional real manifolds with corners
 49  
 50  With these definitions at hand, to invoke an `n`-dimensional real manifold without boundary,
 51  one could use
 52  
 53    `variables {n : â„•} {M : Type*} [topological_space M] [manifold (euclidean_space n)]
 54     [smooth_manifold_with_corners (model_with_corners_self â„ (euclidean_space n)) M]`.
 55  
 56  However, this is not the recommended way: a theorem proved using this assumption would not apply
 57  for instance to the tangent space of such a manifold, which is modelled on
 58  `(euclidean_space n) Ã— (euclidean_space n)` and not on `euclidean_space (2 * n)`! In the same way,
 59  it would not apply to product manifolds, modelled on `(euclidean_space n) Ã— (euclidean_space m)`.
 60  The right invocation does not focus on one specific construction, but on all constructions sharing
 61  the right properties, like
 62  
 63    `variables {E : Type*} [normed_group E] [normed_space â„ E] [finite_dimensional â„ E]
 64    {I : model_with_corners â„ E E} [I.boundaryless]
 65    {M : Type*} [topological_space M] [manifold E M] [smooth_manifold_with_corners I M]`
 66  
 67  Here, `I.boundaryless` is a typeclass property ensuring that there is no boundary (this is for
 68  instance the case for model_with_corners_self, or products of these). Note that one could consider
 69  as a natural assumption to only use the trivial model with corners `model_with_corners_self â„ E`,
 70  but again in product manifolds the natural model with corners will not be this one but the product
 71  one (and they are not defeq as `(Î»p : E Ã— F, (p.1, p.2))` is not defeq to the identity). So, it is
 72  important to use the above incantation to maximize the applicability of theorems.
 73  
 74  ## Implementation notes
 75  
 76  We want to talk about manifolds modelled on a vector space, but also on manifolds with
 77  boundary, modelled on a half space (or even manifolds with corners). For the latter examples,
 78  we still want to define smooth functions, tangent bundles, and so on. As smooth functions are
 79  well defined on vector spaces or subsets of these, one could take for model space a subtype of a
 80  vector space. With the drawback that the whole vector space itself (which is the most basic
 81  example) is not directly a subtype of itself: the inclusion of `univ : set E` in `set E` would
 82  show up in the definition, instead of `id`.
 83  
 84  A good abstraction covering both cases it to have a vector
 85  space `E` (with basic example the Euclidean space), a model space H``  (with basic example the upper
 86  half space), and an embedding of `H` into `E` (which can be the identity for `H = E`, or
 87  `subtype.val` for manifolds with corners). We say that the pair `(E, H)` with their embedding is a
 88  model with corners, and we encompass all the relevant properties (in particular the fact that the
 89  image of `H` in `E` should have unique differentials) in the definition of `model_with_corners`.
 90  
 91  We concentrate on `C^âˆ` manifolds: all the definitions work equally well for `C^n` manifolds, but
 92  later on it is a pain to carry all over the smoothness parameter, especially when one wants to deal
 93  with `C^k` functions as there would be additional conditions `k â‰¤ n` everywhere. Since one deals
 94  almost all the time with `C^âˆ` (or analytic) manifolds, this seems to be a reasonable choice that
 95  one could revisit later if needed. `C^k` manifolds are still available, but they should be called
 96  using `has_groupoid M (times_cont_diff_groupoid k I)` where `I` is the model with corners.
 97  
 98  I have considered using the model with corners `I` as a typeclass argument, possibly `out_param`, to
 99  get lighter notations later on, but it did not turn out right, as on `E Ã— F` there are two natural
100  model with corners, the trivial (identity) one, and the product one, and they are not defeq and one
101  needs to indicate to Lean which one we want to use.
102  This means that when talking on objects on manifolds one will most often need to specify the model
103  with corners one is using. For instance, the tangent bundle will be `tangent_bundle I M` and the
104  derivative will be `mfderiv I I' f`, instead of the more natural notations `tangent_bundle ğ•œ M` and
105  `mfderiv ğ•œ f` (the field has to be explicit anyway, as some manifolds could be considered both as
106  real and complex manifolds).
107  -/

418  ### Extended charts
419  
420  In a smooth manifold with corners, the model space is the space `H`. However, we will also
421  need to use extended charts taking values in the model vector space `E`. These extended charts are
422  not `local_homeomorph` as the target is not open in `E` in general, but we can still register them
423  as `local_equiv`.
424  -/
425  
426  /-- The preferred extended chart on a manifold with corners around a point `x`, from a neighborhood
427  of `x` to the model vector space. -/
